                    <!--AK 21.07.2023 headline checked-->
                    <heading>Defence</heading>
                    <p id="HU.DIR.781">
          Compulsory military service was abolished in November 2004. As assessed at November 2023, the active armed forces numbered 32,150, including land forces of 10,450, an air force of 5,750 and 15,950 joint-forces troops. Reservists totalled 20,000. In 1999 Hungary became a member of the 
          <xr pageref="N" ref="NATO.IO">North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO)</xr>
          . A new NATO Force Integration Unit was inaugurated in Székesfehérvár, in western Hungary, in November 2016. In 2017 Hungary launched a 10-year programme to modernize the armed forces. In April 2020 a new National Security Strategy was published, and a new National Military Strategy followed in June 2021. In January 2022 a Cyber- and Information Operations Centre was created. Following the Russian Federation’s invasion of Ukraine in February, NATO agreed to establish four new multinational battlegroups in Hungary, Bulgaria, Romania and Slovakia. The battlegroup based in Tata numbered approximately 1,054 troops at November. In 2023 the Government announced that it was to despatch troops to Chad to assist the authorities there to respond to security challenges.
        </p>
